 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nThus we have shown that $\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR \ne \O \implies \tuple {x, y} \in \RR$.\nTherefore, by the [[Rule of Transposition]]: 
 :$\tuple {x, y} \notin \RR \implies \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O$\nNow we show that: 
 :$\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O \implies \tuple {x, y} \notin \RR$\nSuppose $\tuple {x, y} \in \RR$. 
 {{begin-eqn}} 
 {{eqn | o = 
 | r = y \in \eqclass y \RR 
 | c = {{Defof|Equivalence Class}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = 
