 | c = [[Definition:By Hypothesis|by hypothesis]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = y \in \eqclass x \RR 
 | c = {{Defof|Equivalence Class}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = y \in \eqclass x \RR \land y \in \eqclass y \RR 
 | c = [[Rule of Conjunction]] 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = y \in \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR 
 | c = {{Defof|Set Intersection}} 
 }}\n{{eqn | o = \leadsto 
 | r = \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR \ne \O 
 | c = {{Defof|Empty Set}} 
 }} 
 {{end-eqn}}\nThus we have shown that: 
 :$\tuple {x, y} \in \RR \implies \eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR \ne \O$\nTherefore, by the [[Rule of Transposition]]: 
 :$\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O \implies \paren {x, y} \notin \RR$\nUsing the rule of [[Biconditional Introduction]] on these results: 
 :$\eqclass x \RR \cap \eqclass y \RR = \O \iff \paren {x, y} \notin \RR$ 
 and the proof is complete.

